{"key":"post-9407783","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>9407783</id>\n<content>Unless the lids seal airtight, you don't need holes.&amp;nbsp; You'll get gas exchange from around the edges.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The statement that the holes need to be even with the substrate is incorrect.&amp;nbsp; The mycelium will produce heat as it grows, and this will in turn cause turbulence that will push the CO2 around and out whatever openings are there.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;It really makes little difference if you protect the sides from light or not.&amp;nbsp; The mycelium doesn't just pin where light hits it.&amp;nbsp; Air exchange is the number 1 pinning trigger, so once the substrate pulls away from the edges, it will side-pin whether you cover them or not.&amp;nbsp; Even black trays will side pin. &lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>9407809</next>\n<prev>9406830</prev>\n<first>9406398</first>\n<last>9407863</last>\n<when>1228953665</when>\n<utime>12/11/08 02:01 AM</utime>\n</post>"}